# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-address-translation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] An **application-level gateway** (**ALG**, also known as **application-layer gateway**, **application gateway**, **application proxy**, or **application-level proxy**) is a security component that augments a firewall or NAT employed in a mobile network.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] It allows customized NAT traversal filters to be plugged into the gateway to support address and port translation for certain application layer "control/data" protocols such as FTP, BitTorrent, SIP, RTSP, file transfer in IM applications.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] In order for these protocols to work through NAT or a firewall, either the application has to know about an address/port number combination that allows incoming packets, or the NAT has to monitor the control traffic and open up port mappings (*firewall pinholes*) dynamically as required.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] Legitimate application data can thus be passed through the security checks of the firewall or NAT that would have otherwise restricted the traffic for not meeting its limited filter criteria.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] Deep packet inspection of all the packets handled by ALGs over a given network makes this functionality possible.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] An ALG understands the protocol used by the specific applications that it supports.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] For instance, for Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) Back-to-Back User agent (B2BUA), an ALG can allow firewall traversal with SIP.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] If the firewall has its SIP traffic terminated on an ALG then the responsibility for permitting SIP sessions passes to the ALG instead of the firewall.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] An ALG can solve another major SIP headache: NAT traversal.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] Basically a NAT with a built-in ALG can rewrite information within the SIP messages and can hold address bindings until the session terminates.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] A SIP ALG will also handle SDP in the body of SIP messages (which is used ubiquitously in VoIP to set up media endpoints), since SDP also contains literal IP addresses and ports that must be translated.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] It is common for SIP ALG on some equipment to interfere with other technologies that try to solve the same problem, and various providers recommend turning it off.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] An ALG is very similar to a proxy server, as it sits between the client and real server, facilitating the exchange.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] There seems to be an industry convention that an ALG does its job without the application being configured to use it, by intercepting the messages.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] A proxy, on the other hand, usually needs to be configured in the client application.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] The client is then explicitly aware of the proxy and connects to it, rather than the real server.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] The *Application Layer Gateway* service in Microsoft Windows provides support for third-party plugins that allow network protocols to pass through the Windows Firewall and work behind it and Internet Connection Sharing.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] ALG plugins can open ports and change data that is embedded in packets, such as ports and IP addresses.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] Windows Server 2003 also includes an ALG FTP plugin.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] The ALG FTP plugin is designed to support active FTP sessions through the NAT engine in Windows.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] To do this, the ALG FTP plugin redirects all traffic that passes through the NAT and that is destined for port 21 (FTP control port) to a private listening port in the 3000–5000 range on the Microsoft *loopback adapter*.
[src:network-address-translation/application-level-gateway] The ALG FTP plugin then monitors/updates traffic on the FTP control channel so that the FTP plugin can plumb port mappings through the NAT for the FTP data channels.
[src:network-address-translation/carrier-grade-nat] Carrier-grade NAT is often used for mitigating IPv4 address exhaustion.
[src:network-address-translation/carrier-grade-nat] One use scenario of CGN has been labeled as **NAT444**, because some customer connections to Internet services on the public Internet would pass through three different IPv4 addressing domains: the customer's own private network, the carrier's private network and the public Internet.
[src:network-address-translation/carrier-grade-nat] Another CGN scenario is Dual-Stack Lite, in which the carrier's network uses IPv6 and thus only two IPv4 addressing domains are needed.
[src:network-address-translation/carrier-grade-nat] CGN may also be applied using ISP-level NAT64 translators in combination with 464XLAT, which eliminates IPv4 entirely at the residential network.
[src:network-address-translation/carrier-grade-nat] CGN techniques were first used in 2000 to accommodate the immediate need for large numbers of IPv4 addresses in General Packet Radio Service (GPRS) deployments of mobile networks.
[src:network-address-translation/carrier-grade-nat] Estimated CGN deployments increased from 1,200 in 2014 to 3,400 in 2016, with 28.85% of the studied deployments appearing to be in mobile operator networks.
[src:network-address-translation/carrier-grade-nat] If an ISP deploys a CGN, and uses RFC 1918 address space to number customer gateways, the risk of address collision, and therefore routing failures, arises when the customer network already uses an RFC 1918 address space.
[src:network-address-translation/carrier-grade-nat] IETF published RFC 6598, detailing a shared address space for use in ISP CGN deployments that can handle the same network prefixes occurring both on inbound and outbound interfaces.
[src:network-address-translation/carrier-grade-nat] ARIN returned address space to the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) for this allocation.
[src:network-address-translation/carrier-grade-nat] Devices evaluating whether an IPv4 address is public must be updated to recognize the new address space.
[src:network-address-translation/carrier-grade-nat] Allocating more private IPv4 address space for NAT devices might postpone the need to transition to IPv6.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] IPv4 uses a 32-bit address space which provides 4,294,967,296 (232) unique addresses, but large blocks are reserved for special networking purposes.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] This quantity of unique addresses is not large enough to meet the needs of the global Internet, which has caused a significant issue known as IPv4 address exhaustion during the ongoing transition to IPv6.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The Internet Protocol ("IP") is the protocol that defines and enables internetworking at the internet layer of the Internet Protocol Suite.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] It gives the Internet a global-scale logical addressing system which allows the routing of IP data packets from a source host to the next router that is one hop closer to the intended destination host on another network.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] IPv4 is a connectionless protocol, and operates on a best-effort delivery model, in that it does not guarantee delivery, nor does it assure proper sequencing or avoidance of duplicate delivery.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] These aspects may be addressed by upper layer transport protocols, such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or the QUIC protocol.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Earlier versions of TCP/IP were a combined specification through TCP/IPv3.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] With IPv4, the Internet Protocol became a separate specification.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Internet Protocol version 4 is described in IETF publication RFC 791 (September 1981), replacing an earlier definition of January 1980 (RFC 760).
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In March 1982, the US Department of Defense decided on the Internet Protocol Suite (TCP/IP) as the standard for all military computer networking.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In the late 1980s, it became apparent that the pool of available IPv4 addresses was depleting at a rate that was not initially anticipated in the original design of the network.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The main market forces that accelerated address depletion beginning in the 1990s included the rapidly growing number of Internet users, who increasingly used mobile computing devices, such as laptop computers, and personal digital assistants (PDAs), and smart phones with IP data services.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In addition, high-speed Internet access was based on always-on devices.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] By the mid-1990s, NAT was used pervasively in network access provider systems, along with strict usage-based allocation policies at the regional and local Internet registries.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The primary address pool of the Internet, maintained by IANA, was exhausted on 3 February 2011, when the last five blocks were allocated to the five RIRs.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] APNIC was the first RIR to exhaust its regional pool on 15 April 2011, except for a small amount of address space reserved for the transition technologies to IPv6, which is to be allocated under a restricted policy.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The long-term solution to address exhaustion was the 1998 specification of a new version of the Internet Protocol, IPv6.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] It provides a vastly increased address space, but also allows improved route aggregation across the Internet, and offers large subnetwork allocations of a minimum of 264 host addresses to end users.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] However, IPv4 is not directly interoperable with IPv6, so IPv4-only hosts cannot directly communicate with IPv6-only hosts.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] With the phase-out of the 6bone experimental network starting in 2004, permanent formal deployment of IPv6 commenced in 2006.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Completion of IPv6 deployment is expected to take considerable time, so that intermediate transition technologies are necessary to permit hosts to participate in the Internet using both versions of the protocol.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] IPv4 uses 32-bit addresses which limits the address space to 4294967296 (232) addresses.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] IPv4 reserves special address blocks for private networks (224 + 220 + 216 ≈ 18 million addresses) and multicast addresses (228 ≈ 268 million addresses).
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] IPv4 addresses may be represented in any notation expressing a 32-bit integer value.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] They are most often written in dot-decimal notation, which consists of four octets of the address expressed individually in decimal numbers (without any extra leading zeros) and separated by periods.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] For example, the quad-dotted IP address in the illustration (*172.16.254.1*) represents the 32-bit decimal number 2886794753, which in hexadecimal format is 0xAC10FE01.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] CIDR notation combines the address with its routing prefix in a compact format, in which the address is followed by a slash character (/) and the count of leading consecutive *1* bits in the routing prefix (subnet mask).
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Other address representations were in common use when classful networking was practiced.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] For example, the loopback address *127.0.0.1* was commonly written as *127.1*, given that it belongs to a class-A network with eight bits for the network mask and 24 bits for the host number.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] When fewer than four numbers were specified in the address in dotted notation, the last value was treated as an integer of as many bytes as are required to fill out the address to four octets.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In the original design of IPv4, an IP address was divided into two parts: the network identifier was the most significant octet of the address, and the host identifier was the rest of the address.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The latter was also called the *rest field*.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] This structure permitted a maximum of 256 network identifiers, which was quickly found to be inadequate.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] To overcome this limit, the most-significant address octet was redefined in 1981 to create *network classes*, in a system which later became known as *classful* networking.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The revised system defined five classes.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Classes A, B, and C had different bit lengths for network identification.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The rest of the address was used as previously to identify a host within a network.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Because of the different sizes of fields in different classes, each network class had a different capacity for addressing hosts.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In addition to the three classes for addressing hosts, Class D was defined for multicast addressing, and Class E was reserved for future applications.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Dividing existing classful networks into subnets began in 1985 with the publication of RFC 950.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] This division was made more flexible with the introduction of variable-length subnet masks (VLSM) in RFC 1109 in 1987.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In 1993, based on this work, RFC 1517 introduced Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR), which expressed the number of bits (from the most significant) as, for instance, */24*, and the class-based scheme was dubbed *classful*, by contrast.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] CIDR was designed to permit repartitioning of any address space so that smaller or larger blocks of addresses could be allocated to users.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The hierarchical structure created by CIDR is managed by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) and the regional Internet registries (RIRs).
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Each RIR maintains a publicly searchable WHOIS database that provides information about IP address assignments.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and IANA have restricted from general use various reserved IP addresses for special purposes.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Notably these addresses are used for multicast traffic and to provide addressing space for unrestricted uses on private networks.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Of the approximately four billion addresses defined in IPv4, about 18 million addresses from three ranges are reserved for use in private networks as outlined by RFC 1918.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Packets with addresses in these ranges are not routable in the public Internet; they are ignored by all public routers.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Therefore, private hosts cannot directly communicate with public networks, but require network address translation at a routing gateway for this purpose.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Additionally, encapsulated packets may be encrypted for transmission across public networks to secure the data.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] IANA has reserved the address block 192.0.0.0/24 for special assignments.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] RFC 3927 defines the special address block 169.254.0.0/16 for link-local addressing.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] These addresses are only valid on the link (such as a local network segment or point-to-point connection) directly connected to a host that uses them.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Like private addresses, these addresses cannot be the source or destination of packets traversing the Internet.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] These addresses are primarily used for address autoconfiguration (Zeroconf) when a host cannot obtain an IP address from a DHCP server or other internal configuration methods.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] When the address block was reserved, no standards existed for address autoconfiguration.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Microsoft created an implementation called Automatic Private IP Addressing (APIPA), which was deployed on millions of machines and became a de facto standard.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Many years later, in May 2005, the IETF defined a formal standard in RFC 3927, entitled *Dynamic Configuration of IPv4 Link-Local Addresses*.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] IP packets whose source addresses belong to this network should never appear outside a host.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Packets received on a non-loopback interface with a loopback source or destination address must be dropped.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In every subnet, both the all-zeros and all-ones host addresses are reserved.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The all-zeros host address is used to identify a given subnet.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The highest address of every subnet, with all host bits set to *1*, is the local broadcast address for sending messages to all devices on the subnet simultaneously.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] For networks of size */24* or larger, the broadcast address in dot-decimal notation always ends in *255*.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] However, this does not mean that every address ending in 0 or 255 cannot be used as a host address.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Also, *192.168.0.0* is the network identifier and must not be assigned to an interface.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In the past, conflict between network addresses and broadcast addresses arose because some software used non-standard broadcast addresses with zeros instead of ones.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In networks smaller than */24*, broadcast addresses do not necessarily end with 255.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] As a special case, a */31* network has capacity for just two hosts.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] These networks are typically used for point-to-point connections.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] There is no network identifier or broadcast address for these networks.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Hosts on the Internet are usually known by names, e.g., www.example.com, not primarily by their IP address, which is used for routing and network interface identification.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The use of domain names requires translating, called *resolving*, them to addresses and vice versa.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] This is analogous to looking up a phone number in a phone book using the recipient's name.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The translation between addresses and domain names is performed by the Domain Name System (DNS), a hierarchical, distributed naming system that allows for the subdelegation of namespaces to other DNS servers.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] An unnumbered point-to-point (PtP) link, also called a transit link, is a link that does not have an IP network or subnet number associated with it, but still has an IP address.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] First introduced in 1993, Phil Karn from Qualcomm is credited as the original designer.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The purpose of a transit link is to route datagrams.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] They are used to free IP addresses from a scarce IP address space or to reduce the management of assigning IP and configuration of interfaces.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Previously, every link needed to dedicate a */31* or */30* subnet using 2 or 4 IP addresses per point-to-point link.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] When a link is unnumbered, a *router-id* is used, a single IP address borrowed from a defined (normally a loopback) interface.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The same *router-id* can be used on multiple interfaces.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] One of the disadvantages of unnumbered interfaces is that it is harder to do remote testing and management.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] An IP packet consists of a header section and a data section.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] An IP packet has no data checksum or any other footer after the data section.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Typically, the link layer encapsulates IP packets in frames with a CRC footer that detects most errors.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Many transport-layer protocols carried by IP also have their own error checking.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The IPv4 packet header consists of 14 fields, of which 13 are required.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The 14th field is optional and aptly named: options.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The fields in the header are packed with the most significant byte first (network byte order), and for the diagram and discussion, the most significant bits are considered to come first (MSB 0 bit numbering).
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The most significant bit is numbered 0, so the version field is actually found in the four most significant bits of the first byte, for example.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The IHL field contains the size of the IPv4 header; it has 4 bits that specify the number of 32-bit words in the header.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] which indicates a length of 5 × 32 bits = 160 bits = 20 bytes.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] As a 4-bit field, the maximum value is 15; this means that the maximum size of the IPv4 header is 15 × 32 bits = 480 bits = 60 bytes.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Real-time data streaming makes use of the DSCP field.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] (VoIP), which is used for interactive voice services.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] ECN is an optional feature available when both endpoints support it and effective when also supported by the underlying network.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] field defines the entire packet size in bytes, including header and data.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The minimum size is 20 bytes (header without data) and the maximum is 65,535 bytes.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] All hosts are required to be able to reassemble datagrams of size up to 576 bytes, but most modern hosts handle much larger packets.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Fragmentation in IPv4 is performed in either the sending host or in routers.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Reassembly is performed at the receiving host.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] This field is an identification field and is primarily used for uniquely identifying the group of fragments of a single IP datagram.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] There are three flags defined within this field.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] This field specifies whether the datagram can be fragmented or not.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] This can be used when sending packets to a host that does not have resources to perform reassembly of fragments.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] If the DF flag is set, and fragmentation is required to route the packet, then the packet is dropped.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] For unfragmented packets, the MF flag is cleared.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] For fragmented packets, all fragments except the last have the MF flag set.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] field, so it can still be differentiated from an unfragmented packet.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] This field specifies the offset of a particular fragment relative to the beginning of the original unfragmented IP datagram.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Fragments are specified in units of 8 bytes, which is why fragment lengths are always a multiple of 8; except the last, which may be smaller.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The fragmentation offset value for the first fragment is always 0.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] – 1) × 8 = 65,528 bytes, with the header length included (65,528 + 20 = 65,548 bytes), supporting fragmentation of packets exceeding the maximum IP length of 65,535 bytes.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] It is specified in seconds, but time intervals less than 1 second are rounded up to 1.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] , the router decrements the TTL field by one.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] sends messages with adjusted TTL values and uses these ICMP time exceeded messages to identify the routers traversed by packets from the source to the destination.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] This field defines the next level protocol used in the data portion of the IP datagram.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] field is used for error checking of the header.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] of the ones' complement sum of all 16-bit words in the header.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] field itself, which is set to zero during computation.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The result should be zero; if a different result is obtained, the device discards the packet.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Consequently, the router must calculate a new header checksum before sending it out again.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Errors in the data portion of the packet are handled separately by the encapsulated protocol.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] have separate checksums that apply to their data.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] field must include sufficient extra 32-bit words to hold all options and any padding needed to ensure that the header contains an integral number of 32-bit words.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] is greater than 5 (i.e., it is from 6 to 15) it means that the options field is present and must be considered.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The list of options may be terminated with the option EOOL (End of Options List, 0x00); this is only necessary if the end of the options would not otherwise coincide with the end of the header.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] since they can expose the network topology or network details.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The Internet Protocol enables traffic between networks.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The design accommodates networks of diverse physical nature; it is independent of the underlying transmission technology used in the link layer.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Networks with different hardware usually vary not only in transmission speed, but also in the maximum transmission unit (MTU).
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] When one network wants to transmit datagrams to a network with a smaller MTU, it may fragment its datagrams.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In IPv4, this function was placed at the Internet Layer and is performed in IPv4 routers, limiting exposure to these issues by hosts.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In contrast, IPv6, the next generation of the Internet Protocol, does not allow routers to perform fragmentation; hosts must perform Path MTU Discovery before sending datagrams.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] When a router receives a packet, it examines the destination address and determines the outgoing interface to use and that interface's MTU.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] If the packet size is bigger than the MTU, and the Do not Fragment (DF) bit in the packet's header is set to 0, then the router may fragment the packet.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The router divides the payload into fragments.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The maximum size of each fragment is the outgoing MTU minus the IP header size (20 bytes minimum; 60 bytes maximum).
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] It is possible that a packet is fragmented at one router and that the fragments are further fragmented at another router.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The total data size is preserved: 2,480 bytes + 2,020 bytes = 4,500 bytes.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Also in this case, the *More Fragments* bit remains 1 for all the fragments that came with 1 in them, and for the last fragment that arrives, it works as usual, that is, the MF bit is set to 0 only in the last one.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] And of course, the Identification field continues to have the same value in all re-fragmented fragments.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] This way, even if fragments are re-fragmented, the receiver knows they have initially all started from the same packet.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The receiver identifies matching fragments using the source and destination addresses, the protocol ID, and the identification field.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The receiver reassembles the data from fragments with the same ID using both the fragment offset and the more fragments flag.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] When the receiver receives the last fragment, which has the *more fragments* flag set to 0, it can calculate the size of the original data payload by multiplying the last fragment's offset by eight and adding the last fragment's data size.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In the given example, this calculation was $495\times 8+540=4{,}500$ bytes.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] When the receiver has all fragments, they can be reassembled in the correct sequence according to the offsets to form the original datagram.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] IP addresses are not tied in any permanent manner to networking hardware and, indeed, in modern operating systems, a network interface can have multiple IP addresses.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In order to properly deliver an IP packet to the destination host on a link, hosts and routers need additional mechanisms to make an association between the hardware address of network interfaces and IP addresses.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] The Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) performs this IP-address-to-hardware-address translation for IPv4.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] In addition, the reverse correlation is often necessary.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] For example, unless an address is preconfigured by an administrator, when an IP host is booted or connected to a network, it needs to determine its IP address.
[src:network-address-translation/ipv4] Protocols for such reverse correlations include Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP), Bootstrap Protocol (BOOTP) and, infrequently, reverse ARP.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] As network address translation modifies the IP address information in packets, NAT implementations may vary in their specific behavior in various addressing cases and their effect on network traffic.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Vendors of equipment containing NAT implementations do not commonly document the specifics of NAT behavior.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) uses 32-bit addresses, capable of uniquely addressing about 4.3 billion devices on the network.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] By 1992, it became evident that this would not be enough.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The 1994 RFC 1631 describes NAT as a "short-term solution" to the two most compelling problems facing the Internet Protocol at that time: IP address depletion and scaling in routing.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The technique also became known as **IP masquerading**, which suggests a technique that hides an entire IP address space, usually consisting of private IP addresses, behind a single IP address in another, usually public address space.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Because of the popularity of this technique to conserve IPv4 address space, the term *NAT* became virtually synonymous with IP masquerading.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] In 1996, port-address translation (PAT) was introduced, which expanded the translation of addresses to include port numbers.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The simplest type of NAT provides a one-to-one translation of IP addresses (RFC 1631).
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] RFC 2663 refers to this type of NAT as *basic NAT*, also called a *one-to-one NAT*.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] In this type of NAT, only the IP addresses, IP header checksum, and any higher-level checksums that include the IP address are changed.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Basic NAT can be used to interconnect two IP networks with incompatible addresses.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Most network address translators map multiple private hosts to one publicly exposed IP address.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] In a typical configuration, a local network uses one of the designated *private* IP address subnets (RFC 1918).
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The network has a router having network interfaces on both the private and the public networks.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The public address is typically assigned by an Internet service provider.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] As traffic passes from the private network to the Internet, NAT translates the source address in each packet from a private address to the router's public address.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The NAT facility tracks each active connection.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] When the router receives inbound traffic from the Internet, it uses the connection tracking data obtained during the outbound phase to determine to which private address it should forward the reply.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Packets passing from the private network to the public network will have their source address modified, while packets passing from the public network back to the private network will have their destination address modified.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] To avoid ambiguity in how replies are translated, further modifications to the packets are required.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The vast bulk of Internet traffic uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] For these protocols, the port numbers are changed so that the combination of IP address (within the IP header) and port number (within the Transport Layer header) on the returned packet can be unambiguously mapped to the corresponding private network destination.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] RFC 2663 uses the term **network address and port translation** (**NAPT**) for this type of NAT.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Other names include **port address translation** (**PAT**), *IP masquerading*, *NAT overload*, and *many-to-one NAT*.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] This is the most common type of NAT and has become synonymous with the term *NAT* in common usage.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] This method allows communication through the router only when the conversation originates in the private network, since the initial originating transmission establishes the required information in the translation tables.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Thus, a web browser within the private network is able to browse websites that are outside the network, whereas web browsers outside the network are unable to browse a website hosted within.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Protocols not based on TCP and UDP require other translation techniques.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The primary benefit of one-to-many NAT is mitigation of IPv4 address exhaustion by allowing entire networks to be connected to the Internet using a single public IP address.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Network address and port translation may be implemented in several ways.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Some applications that use IP address information may need to determine the external address of a network address translator.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] This is the address that its communication peers in the external network detect.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Furthermore, it may be necessary to examine and categorize the type of mapping in use, for example, when it is desired to set up a direct communication path between two clients, both of which are behind separate NAT gateways.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] For this purpose, RFC 3489 specified the protocol *Simple Traversal of UDP over NATs* (STUN) in 2003.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] It classified NAT implementations as *full-cone NAT*, *(address) restricted-cone NAT*, *port-restricted cone NAT* or *symmetric NAT*, and proposed a methodology for testing a device accordingly.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] However, these procedures have since been deprecated from standards status, as the methods are inadequate to correctly assess many devices.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] RFC 5389 standardized new methods in 2008 and the acronym *STUN* since represents the new title of the specification: *Session Traversal Utilities for NAT*.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] As many NAT implementations combine multiple types, it is better to refer to specific individual NAT behavior instead of using the Cone/Symmetric terminology.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] RFC 4787 attempts to alleviate confusion by introducing standardized terminology for observed behaviors.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] For the first bullet in each row of the above table, the RFC would characterize Full-Cone, Restricted-Cone, and Port-Restricted-Cone NATs as having an *Endpoint-Independent Mapping*, whereas it would characterize a Symmetric NAT as having an *Address- and Port-Dependent Mapping*.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Other classifications of NAT behavior mentioned in the RFC include whether they preserve ports, when and how mappings are refreshed, whether external mappings can be used by internal hosts (i.e., its hairpinning behavior), and the level of determinism NATs exhibit when applying all these rules.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Specifically, most NATs combine *symmetric NAT* for outgoing connections with *static port mapping*, where incoming packets addressed to the external address and port are redirected to a specific internal address and port.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] RFC 4787 distinguishes between NAT mapping and NAT filtering.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Section 4.1 of the RFC covers NAT mapping and specifies the translation of an external IP address and port number into an internal IP address and port number.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Section 5 of the RFC covers NAT filtering and describes the criteria used by the NAT to filter packets originating from specific external endpoints.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The options are endpoint-independent filtering, address-dependent filtering and address- and port-dependent filtering.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Endpoint-independent filtering is recommended where maximum application transparency is required while address-dependent filtering is recommended where more stringent filtering behavior is most important.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Some NAT devices are not compliant with RFC 4787 as they treat NAT mapping and filtering in the same way, so that their configuration option for changing the NAT filtering method also changes the NAT mapping method (e.g., Netgate TNSR Archived 2024-01-30 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] NAT traversal problems arise when peers behind different NATs try to communicate.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] One way to solve this problem is to use port forwarding.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Another way is to use various NAT traversal techniques.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The most popular technique for TCP NAT traversal is TCP hole punching.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] TCP hole punching requires the NAT to follow the *port preservation* design for TCP.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] For a given outgoing TCP communication, the same port numbers are used on both sides of the NAT.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] NAT port preservation for outgoing TCP connections is crucial for TCP NAT traversal because, under TCP, one port can only be used for one communication at a time.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Programs that bind distinct TCP sockets to ephemeral ports for each TCP communication make NAT port prediction impossible for TCP.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] On the other hand, for UDP, NATs do not need port preservation.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Indeed, multiple UDP communications (each with a distinct endpoint) can occur on the same source port, and applications usually reuse the same UDP socket to send packets to distinct hosts.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] This makes port prediction straightforward, as it is the same source port for each packet.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Furthermore, port preservation in NAT for TCP allows P2P protocols to offer less complexity and less latency because there is no need to use a third party (like STUN) to discover the NAT port since the application itself already knows the NAT port.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Every TCP and UDP packet contains a source port number and a destination port number.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Each of those packets is encapsulated in an IP packet, whose IP header contains a source IP address and a destination IP address.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The IP address/protocol/port number triple defines an association with a network socket.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] For publicly accessible services such as web and mail servers, the port number is important.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] For example, port 443 connects through a socket to the web server software and port 465 to a mail server's SMTP daemon.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The IP address of a public server is also important, similar in global uniqueness to a postal address or telephone number.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Both the IP address and port number must be correctly known by all hosts wishing to communicate successfully.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Private IP addresses as described in RFC 1918, are usable only on private networks not directly connected to the Internet.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Ports are endpoints of communication unique to that host, so a connection through the NAT device is maintained by the combined mapping of port and IP address.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] A private address on the inside of the NAT is mapped to an external public address.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Port address translation (PAT) resolves conflicts that arise when multiple hosts happen to use the same source port number to establish different external connections at the same time.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] With NAT, all communications sent to external hosts actually contain the *external* IP address and port information of the NAT device instead of internal host IP addresses or port numbers.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] NAT only translates IP addresses and ports of its internal hosts, hiding the true endpoint of an internal host on a private network.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] When a computer on the private (internal) network sends an IP packet to the external network, the NAT device replaces the internal source IP address in the packet header with the external IP address of the NAT device.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] PAT may then assign the connection a port number from a pool of available ports, inserting this port number in the source port field.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The packet is then forwarded to the external network.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The NAT device then makes an entry in a translation table containing the internal IP address, original source port, and the translated source port.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Subsequent packets from the same internal source IP address and port number are translated to the same external source IP address and port number.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The computer receiving a packet that has undergone NAT establishes a connection to the port and IP address specified in the altered packet, oblivious to the fact that the supplied address is being translated.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Upon receiving a packet from the external network, the NAT device searches the translation table based on the destination port in the packet header.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] If a match is found, the destination IP address and port number are replaced with the values found in the table and the packet is forwarded to the inside network.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Otherwise, if the destination port number of the incoming packet is not found in the translation table, the packet is dropped or rejected because the PAT device doesn't know where to send it.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Network address translation can be used to mitigate IP address overlap.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Address overlap occurs when hosts in different networks with the same IP address space try to reach the same destination host.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The destination host experiences traffic apparently arriving from the same network, and intermediate routers have no way to determine where reply traffic should be sent to.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The solution is either renumbering to eliminate overlap or network address translation.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] forward client requests to a set of server computers to manage the workload of each server.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Network address translation may be used to map a representative IP address of the server cluster to specific hosts that service the request.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] IEEE Reverse Address and Port Translation (RAPT or RAT) allows a host whose real IP address changes from time to time to remain reachable as a server via a fixed home IP address.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Cisco's RAPT implementation is PAT or NAT overloading and maps multiple private IP addresses to a single public IP address.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Multiple addresses can be mapped to a single address because each private address is tracked by a port number.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] PAT uses unique source port numbers on the inside global IP address to distinguish between translations.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] PAT attempts to preserve the original source port.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] If this source port is already used, PAT assigns the first available port number starting from the beginning of the appropriate port group 0–511, 512–1023, or 1024–65535.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] When there are no more ports available and there is more than one external IP address configured, PAT moves to the next IP address to try to allocate the original source port again.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] This process continues until it runs out of available ports and external IP addresses.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Mapping of Address and Port is a Cisco proposal that combines Address plus Port translation with tunneling of the IPv4 packets over an ISP provider's internal IPv6 network.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] In effect, it is an (almost) stateless alternative to carrier-grade NAT and DS-Lite that pushes the IPv4 address/port translation function (and the maintenance of NAT state) entirely into the existing customer premises equipment NAT implementation.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Thus avoiding the NAT444 and statefulness problems of carrier-grade NAT, and also provides a transition mechanism for the deployment of native IPv6 at the same time with very little added complexity.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Hosts behind NAT-enabled routers do not have end-to-end connectivity and cannot participate in some internet protocols.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Services that require the initiation of TCP connections from the outside network, or that use stateless protocols such as those using UDP, can be disrupted.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Unless the NAT router makes a specific effort to support such protocols, incoming packets cannot reach their destination.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Some protocols can accommodate one instance of NAT between participating hosts ("passive mode" FTP, for example), sometimes with the assistance of an application-level gateway (see § Applications affected by NAT), but fail when both systems are separated from the internet by NAT.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The use of NAT also complicates tunneling protocols such as IPsec because NAT modifies values in the headers, which interfere with the integrity checks done by IPsec and other tunneling protocols.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] End-to-end connectivity has been a core principle of the Internet, supported, for example, by the Internet Architecture Board.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Current Internet architectural documents observe that NAT is a violation of the end-to-end principle, but that NAT does have a valid role in careful design.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] There is considerably more concern with the use of IPv6 NAT, and many IPv6 architects believe IPv6 was intended to remove the need for NAT.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] An implementation that only tracks ports can be quickly depleted by internal applications that use multiple simultaneous connections, such as an HTTP request for a web page with many embedded objects.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] This problem can be mitigated by tracking the destination IP address in addition to the port, thus sharing a single local port with many remote hosts.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] This additional tracking increases implementation complexity and computing resources at the translation device.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Because the internal addresses are all disguised behind one publicly accessible address, it is impossible for external hosts to directly initiate a connection to a particular internal host.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Applications such as VOIP, videoconferencing, and other peer-to-peer applications must use NAT traversal techniques to function.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Pure NAT, operating on IP alone, may or may not correctly parse protocols with payloads containing information about IP, such as ICMP.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] This depends on whether the payload is interpreted by a host on the *inside* or *outside* of the translation.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Basic protocols such as TCP and UDP cannot function properly unless NAT takes action beyond the network layer.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] IP packets have a checksum in each packet header, which provides error detection only for the header.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] IP datagrams may become fragmented and it is necessary for a NAT to reassemble these fragments to allow correct recalculation of higher-level checksums and correct tracking of which packets belong to which connection.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] TCP and UDP have a checksum that covers all the data they carry, as well as the TCP or UDP header, plus a *pseudo-header* that contains the source and destination IP addresses of the packet carrying the TCP or UDP header.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] For an originating NAT to pass TCP or UDP successfully, it must recompute the TCP or UDP header checksum based on the translated IP addresses, not the original ones, and put that checksum into the TCP or UDP header of the first packet of the fragmented set of packets.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Alternatively, the originating host may perform path MTU Discovery to determine the packet size that can be transmitted without fragmentation and then set the *don't fragment* (DF) bit in the appropriate packet header field.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] This is only a one-way solution, because the responding host can send packets of any size, which may be fragmented before reaching the NAT.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Destination network address translation (DNAT) is a technique for transparently changing the destination IP address of a routed packet and performing the inverse function for any replies.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Any router situated between two endpoints can perform this transformation of the packet.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] DNAT is commonly used to publish a service located in a private network on a publicly accessible IP address.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] This use of DNAT is also called port forwarding, or DMZ when used on an entire server, which becomes exposed to the WAN, becoming analogous to an undefended military demilitarized zone (DMZ).
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Secure network address translation (SNAT) is part of Microsoft's Internet Security and Acceleration Server and is an extension to the NAT driver built into Microsoft Windows Server.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] It provides connection tracking and filtering for the additional network connections needed for the FTP, ICMP, H.323, and PPTP protocols as well as the ability to configure a transparent HTTP proxy server.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Dynamic NAT, just like static NAT, is not common in smaller networks but is found within larger corporations with complex networks.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Where static NAT provides a one-to-one internal to public static IP address mapping, dynamic NAT uses a *group* of public IP addresses.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] If a packet is sent to *203.0.113.1* by a computer at *192.168.1.100*, the packet would normally be routed to the default gateway (the router).
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] A router with the NAT loopback feature detects that *203.0.113.1* is the address of its WAN interface, and treats the packet as if coming from that interface.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] It determines the destination for that packet, based on DNAT (port forwarding) rules for the destination.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] If the data were sent to port 80 and a DNAT rule exists for port 80 directed to *192.168.1.2*, then the host at that address receives the packet.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] If no applicable DNAT rule is available, the router drops the packet.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] An ICMP Destination Unreachable reply may be sent.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] If any DNAT rules were present, address translation is still in effect; the router still rewrites the source IP address in the packet.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Because the source address is part of the same broadcast domain as the server, it will respond with a packet destined directly to the local computer on layer 2, without involving the router.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] As the local computer did not expect any traffic from *192.168.1.2* (the local address of the server), but from *203.0.113.1*, the address that it actually intended to connect to, it will silently drop the response.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] To enable two-way communication using the external address between these hosts, an SNAT rule must be configured.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Such a rule specifies that traffic received from the local network and destined to the server (to its local address, after rewriting) should have its source address rewritten to an address of the router.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] This way, the response of the server will be sent to the router, which is then able to apply the reverse SNAT and DNAT transformations and send the expected response back to the local computer.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Thus, two-way communication is possible between hosts inside the LAN network via the public IP address, as long as appropriate NAT rules are set up.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Network address translation is not commonly used in IPv6 because one of the design goals of IPv6 is to restore end-to-end network connectivity.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The large addressing space of IPv6 obviates the need to conserve addresses and every device can be given a unique globally routable address.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Use of unique local addresses in combination with network prefix translation can achieve results similar to NAT.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The large addressing space of IPv6 can still be defeated, depending on the actual prefix length given by the carrier.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] It is not uncommon to be handed a /64 prefix – the smallest recommended subnet – for an entire home network, requiring a variety of techniques to be used to manually subdivide the range for all devices to remain reachable.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] In such cases, it may be required to use full network address and port translation (NAPT) on IPv6, usually referred to as NAT66, where an IPv6 ULA prefix is masqueraded down to a single IPv6 global unique address (GUA).
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The APNIC blog outlines a case where the author was only provided a single address (/128).
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Some application layer protocols, such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP) and Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), send explicit network addresses within their application data.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] File Transfer Protocol in active mode, for example, uses separate connections for control traffic (commands) and for data traffic (file contents).
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] When requesting a file transfer, the host making the request identifies the corresponding data connection by its network layer and transport layer addresses.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] If the host making the request lies behind a simple NAT firewall, the translation of the IP address or TCP port number makes the information received by the server invalid.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] SIP commonly controls voice over IP calls, and suffer the same problem.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] SIP and its accompanying Session Description Protocol may use multiple ports to set up a connection and transmit a voice stream via Real-time Transport Protocol.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] IP addresses and port numbers are encoded in the payload data and must be known before the traversal of NATs.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Without special techniques, such as STUN, NAT behavior is unpredictable and communications may fail.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Application Layer Gateway (ALG) software or hardware may correct these problems.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] An ALG software module running on a NAT firewall device updates any payload data made invalid by address translation.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] ALGs need to understand the higher-layer protocol that they need to fix, and so each protocol with this problem requires a separate ALG.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] For example, on many Linux systems, there are kernel modules called *connection trackers* that serve to implement ALGs.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] However, ALG cannot work if the protocol data is encrypted.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Another possible solution to this problem is to use NAT traversal techniques using protocols such as STUN or Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE), or proprietary approaches in a session border controller.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] NAT traversal is possible in both TCP- and UDP-based applications, but the UDP-based technique is simpler, more widely understood, and more compatible with legacy NATs.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] In either case, the high-level protocol must be designed with NAT traversal in mind, and it does not work reliably across symmetric NATs or other poorly behaved legacy NATs.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Other possibilities are Port Control Protocol (PCP), NAT Port Mapping Protocol (NAT-PMP), or Internet Gateway Device Protocol but these require the NAT device to implement that protocol.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Most client–server protocols (FTP being the main exception), however, do not send layer 3 contact information and do not require any special treatment by NATs.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] In fact, avoiding NAT complications is practically a requirement when designing new higher-layer protocols today.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] NATs can also cause problems where IPsec encryption is applied and in cases where multiple devices, such as SIP phones are located behind a NAT.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Phones that encrypt their signaling with IPsec encapsulate the port information within an encrypted packet, meaning that NAT devices cannot access and translate the port.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] In these cases, the NAT devices revert to simple NAT operations.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] This means that all traffic returning to the NAT is mapped onto one client, causing service to more than one client behind the NAT to fail.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE) is a NAT traversal technique that does not rely on ALG support.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The DNS protocol vulnerability announced by Dan Kaminsky on July 8, 2008, is indirectly affected by NAT port mapping.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] To avoid DNS cache poisoning, it is highly desirable not to translate UDP source port numbers of outgoing DNS requests from a DNS server behind a firewall that implements NAT.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] The recommended workaround for the DNS vulnerability is to make all caching DNS servers use randomized UDP source ports.
[src:network-address-translation/network-address-translation] If the NAT function de-randomizes the UDP source ports, the DNS server becomes vulnerable.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] The process, which results in the proxy server responding with its own MAC address to an ARP request for a different IP address for proxying purposes, is sometimes referred to as *publishing*.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] The access router gives the dial-up nodes IP addresses in the range 192.168.0.128 – 192.168.0.254; for this example, assume a dial-up node gets IP address 192.168.0.254.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] without being wired into the Ethernet: the access router 'publishes' its own MAC address for 192.168.0.254.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] Now, when another node wired into the Ethernet wants to talk to the dial-up node, it will ask on the network for the MAC address of 192.168.0.254 and find the access router's MAC address.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] It will therefore send its IP packets to the access router, and the access router will know to pass them on to the particular dial-up node.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] All dial-up nodes therefore appear to the wired Ethernet nodes as if they are wired into the same Ethernet subnet.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] Certain applications may require multiple IP addresses on the server.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] Provided the addresses have to be from the 10.0.0.0/24 range, the way the problem is solved is through proxy ARP.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] /other virtual server environments) and 'published' on the 10.0.0.2 interface (although many operating systems allow direct allocation of multiple addresses to one interface, thus eliminating the need for such workarounds).
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] In this scenario a firewall can be configured with a single IP address.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] One simple example of a use for this would be placing a firewall in front of a single host or group of hosts on a subnetwork.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] A proxy ARP firewall can be placed in front of the server.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] In this way the server is put behind a firewall without having to make any further changes to the network.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] Disadvantage of proxy ARP include scalability as ARP resolution by a proxy is required for every device routed in this manner, and reliability, as no fallback mechanism is present, and masquerading can be confusing in some environments.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] Proxy ARP can create DoS attacks on networks if misconfigured.
[src:network-address-translation/proxy-arp] Proxy ARP can hide device misconfigurations, such as a missing or incorrect default gateway.
